To simplify \(\sqrt{\tfrac{4}{225}}\), split the root over numerator and denominator:

\[
\sqrt{\frac{4}{225}}
= \frac{\sqrt{4}}{\sqrt{225}}
= \frac{2}{15}.
\]

To simplify \(\displaystyle \sqrt{\frac{360}{361}}\), write it as
\[
\sqrt{\frac{360}{361}}
= \frac{\sqrt{360}}{\sqrt{361}}
= \frac{\sqrt{36\cdot 10}}{19}
= \frac{6\sqrt{10}}{19}.
\] 
So the simplified form is \(\displaystyle \frac{6\sqrt{10}}{19}\).

To simplify \(\frac{8}{1-\sqrt{17}}\), multiply numerator and denominator by the conjugate \(1+\sqrt{17}\):

\[
\frac{8}{1-\sqrt{17}}
\;\times\;
\frac{1+\sqrt{17}}{1+\sqrt{17}}
\;=\;
\frac{8(1+\sqrt{17})}{(1-\sqrt{17})(1+\sqrt{17})}
\;=\;
\frac{8(1+\sqrt{17})}{1-17}
\;=\;
\frac{8(1+\sqrt{17})}{-16}
\;=\;
-\frac{1+\sqrt{17}}{2}.
\]

First note inside the fourth‐root:

\[
\frac{162x^6}{16x^4}
=\frac{162}{16}\;x^{6-4}
=\frac{81}{8}\,x^2.
\]

So
\[
\sqrt[4]{\frac{162x^6}{16x^4}}
=\sqrt[4]{\frac{81}{8}\,x^2}
=\frac{\sqrt[4]{81}\;\sqrt[4]{x^2}}{\sqrt[4]{8}}
=\frac{3\,x^{1/2}}{2^{3/4}}.
\]

You can leave it as 
\[
\frac{3\sqrt{x}}{2^{3/4}},
\]
or if you prefer to “rationalize” the denominator multiply top and bottom by \(2^{1/4}\) to get

\[
\frac{3\sqrt{x}}{2^{3/4}}
\;\cdot\;
\frac{2^{1/4}}{2^{1/4}}
\;=\;
\frac{3\,2^{1/4}\,\sqrt{x}}{2}\,. 
\]

First write everything with rational exponents:

\[
\frac{\sqrt{m\,n^3}}{a^2\sqrt{c^{-3}}}
\;\cdot\;
\frac{a^{-7}n^{-2}}{\sqrt{m^2c^4}}
=
\frac{m^{1/2}n^{3/2}}{a^2\;c^{-3/2}}
\;\cdot\;
\frac{a^{-7}n^{-2}}{m^1c^2}.
\]

Combine factors of each base:

– For \(a\): exponent in numerator is \(-7\), in denominator \(+2\), so total \(a^{-7-2}=a^{-9}\).  
– For \(m\): exponent in numerator \(+\tfrac12\), in denominator \(+1\), so total \(m^{1/2-1}=m^{-1/2}\).  
– For \(n\): exponent in numerator \(+\tfrac32-2=-\tfrac12\).  
– For \(c\): exponent in numerator \(+\tfrac32\), in denominator \(+2\), so total \(c^{3/2-2}=c^{-1/2}\).

Hence the product is
\[
a^{-9}\,m^{-1/2}\,n^{-1/2}\,c^{-1/2}
\;=\;
\frac{1}{a^9\,\sqrt{m\,n\,c}}\,. 
\]
